'''Saint-Acheul''' is a [[Communes of France|commune]] in the [[Somme (department)|Somme]] [[Departments of France|department]] in [[Hauts-de-France]] in northern [[France]]. It is not to be confused with Saint-Acheul, a suburb of [[Amiens]] after which the [[Acheulean]] [[archaeological culture]] of the [[Lower Paleolithic]] is named.
==Geography== The commune is situated some {{Convert|23|mi|km|0}} north of [[Amiens]], on the junction of the D933 and D99e roads, only a few hundred yards from the border with the [[Pas-de-Calais]]
==Population== {{Demography |1962 = 33 |1968 = 50 |1975 = 45 |1982 = 43 |1990 = 34 |1999 = 22 |2006 = 27 |withoutdoublecount = 1962 }}
==History== In the first century AD the Romans settled the area and a monastery was built in St Acheul during the Middle Ages. [[Saint Ulphia]] was a hermit here during the 8th century.
